results.notes:
At the top of Gibraltar Road in the Transverse Range above Santa Barbara.

Thallus a thin rimose crust of mottle grey-white flat areoles. Apothecia common, large, plane, with a thin raised rim, often appearing divided, epruinose or lightly dusted. Epihymenium dark with green tints below into upper hymenium. POL+ crystals scattered in epi and streaked through hymenium. Hymenium hyaline to yellowish. Hypothecium dark brown. Exciple C+R. Thallus and apothecium section in KOH produced a flow of small oil drop/bubbles potentially equating to Fryday (1992) positive confluentic acid test, and also produced reddish halo (see Hollinger 16273 reports K+reddish with small crystals in diducens). L. cerviniicola recently reported from NA (Fryday 2020) would have perlatolic acid instead of confluentic. TLC best for final determination.

results.notes: Lichen found on a slick that was picked up from the forest floor. I was drawn to this lichen because of its numerous apothecia, something that I had not often seen in lichen species before this. Apothecia range in size from around .5mm to 2mm. It is light greenish/grey with white patches on the outer edges. The underside of this lichen is greyish/brown. It is also lacking soredia and isidia when closely examined. I performed a KOH test on the surface of the lichen and the test was positive. I then performed another KOH test on the medullary layer and that test was negative. This told me that it was a Physcia species. I made a slide of an apothecia as shown below. In the slide you can see the distince algal and fungal layers of this lichen, and also the spores inside the asci.
